The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, April 07, 2004  Business Briefs Mumbai, April 6: The income tax department  has served a notice on Tata Sons, the holding company of  Tata Consultancy Services, to pay additional tax of close  to Rs 100 crore on the ground that TCS was not eligible  for certain tax benefits availed by it. Officials said the  company would seek a reassessment of the demand made by  the department. Last week, Wipro received notices to pay  Rs 261 crore. Moscow, April 6: Tata Motors has started  assembling around 400 trucks of 2.8 and 3.8 tons capacity  using component kits from India at the Amur plant in Novouralsk  town in the Ural mountains.  Mumbai, April 6: The rupee closed at  43.74 against the dollar, down six paise from Mondays close  of 43.68. New Delhi, April 6: The mobile phone  user base in the country has crossed 33 million in March.  Reliance topped the list with over 7.2 million users followed  by Bharti with 6.5 million. Calcutta, April 6: Haldia Petrochemicals  Ltd has said it will pay interest for January-March, a release  said. This is in response to an order issued by the debt  recovery tribunal restraining the company from selling and  transferring specified properties for its failure to pay  around Rs 16 crore of interest to Unit Trust on debentures  issued.
